    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-08T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-08T11:00:00-05:00" n="870"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d870">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/7–854: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-08T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 8, 1954—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 573. Repeated information Paris 22, Bonn
                    6. 2 members US Delegation had lunch today with Dr. <persName corresp="#p_FM1"
                        >Martin Fischer</persName>, Senior West German Observer for Geneva
                    Conference. <persName corresp="#p_FM1">Fischer</persName> had just returned from
                    Bonn where he had reported to Chancellor, Foreign Minister, and other officials
                    in Conference. He stated officials in Bonn are very interested in Conference,
                    particularly as it may indirectly influence prospects for <gloss
                        target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>. He referred to, but did not endorse, press
                    speculation that French may trade <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss> for
                    favorable Indochina settlement. In this context, he reported that a few days
                    ago, when he, Chancellor, and Foreign Minister appeared before Foreign Affairs
                    Committee of Bundestag, member of Committee asked why victorious Viet Minh
                    troops had not pressed their advantage and driven French out of <pb facs="1329"
                        n="1303" xml:id="pg_1303"/> Tonkin. Foreign Minister replied that he also
                    would like answer to this question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
